!! Core principle

External tools push content via CLI import (primary) or HTTP POST (fallback). Both paths share a single resolution pipeline that transforms the raw request into a fully-formed tiddler by evaluating template tiddlers whose fields are TW filter expressions. Post-creation side effects are handled by action widgets in the template's `text` field.

!! Data flow (CLI import ŌĆö primary path)

# External tool writes JSON to a file and runs `TIDDLYWIKI_CLI_MODE=1 npx tiddlywiki mywiki --import input.json application/x-rimir-ext-connect`
# `deserializer.js` parses JSON from the file
# Context tiddler titles from the request are loaded from `$tw.wiki`
# `resolve.js` builds variable map (context, timestamp, profile)
# Profile lookup ŌåÆ template tiddler evaluated ŌåÆ base output fields
# Rule evaluation: first-match TW filter ŌåÆ template tiddler(s) evaluated ŌåÆ fields merged
# Explicit `body.fields` override ŌåÆ merge on top
# `body.title` / `body.text` ŌåÆ always win
# Title fallback: `Inbox/<timestamp>` if still missing; default `type` if missing
# Tiddler saved to `$tw.wiki` + written to disk via `saveTiddlerToFileSync`
# ''Post-creation actions'': collected `text` from templates executed as action widgets (with `new-title` variable)
# Any tiddlers modified by actions detected via changeCount diff and persisted to disk
# If a server is running, filesystem-watcher detects the new `.tid` files and syncs to browser

!! Data flow (POST ŌĆö fallback, may be deprecated)

# External tool sends `POST /api/ext-connect/put-tiddler` with JSON body
# `route.js` validates CSRF header and parses body from `state.data`
# Steps 3ŌĆō9 are identical (shared `resolve.js` pipeline)
# Tiddler saved to `$tw.wiki` + syncer mismatch triggers file write on next tick
# Post-creation actions executed; syncer updated for any tiddlers modified by actions
# JSON response returned: `{status, title}`

!! Template tiddler field convention

Template tiddlers define output fields. Each non-reserved field's value is a TW filter expression.

|!Field pattern |!Behavior |
|`out.fieldname` |Strip `out.` prefix ŌåÆ output field name; value evaluated as TW filter |
|non-reserved field |Output field directly; value evaluated as TW filter |
|reserved (`title`, `text`, `type`, `tags`, `created`, `modified`, `creator`, `modifier`, `bag`, `revision`) |Skipped as output |
|`text` (body) |Collected as action widget markup, executed after tiddler creation |

Special handling:

* ''tags output'': all filter results joined via `$tw.utils.stringifyList()` (supports multi-value)
* ''All other fields'': first filter result used as value
* ''Conflict'': if both `out.parent` and `parent` exist, the `out.` version wins

!! Merge order

Fields accumulate through the pipeline. Later stages override earlier ones:

|!Priority |!Source |!Example |
|1 (lowest) |Profile template |`title`, `tags`, `type` from template filter evaluation |
|2 |Rule template(s) |Fields + actions from matched rule's template tiddler(s) |
|3 |Explicit `fields` from body |`{"tags": "Override", "custom": "value"}` |
|4 (highest) |`title` / `text` from body |Always wins if present |
|fallback |Auto-generated title |`Inbox/<timestamp>` |

!! Components

|!Component |!Layer |!Role |
|`route.js` |Server (Node.js) |HTTP POST handler ŌĆö CSRF check, body parse, context loading, save + action execution |
|`deserializer.js` |Server (Node.js) |CLI `--import` handler ŌĆö JSON parse, resolve, disk persistence, action execution |
|`resolve.js` |Server (library) |Shared resolution pipeline ŌĆö variable building, context loading, filter evaluation, template processing, action execution |
|`profiles.tid` |Wiki store (JSON) |Named profile ŌåÆ template tiddler title mapping |
|`rules.tid` |Wiki store (JSON) |Ordered rules: TW filter ŌåÆ template tiddler title(s) |
|`tpl-*.tid` |Wiki store |Template tiddlers with filter-valued fields and action widget text |

!! Rule evaluation

Rules are stored as an ordered JSON array. Evaluation is //first-match wins//:

# Iterate rules in order
# For each rule, evaluate its `filter` against the wiki (with `context-titles` variable)
# Non-empty result = match ŌåÆ evaluate the rule's `templates` in order, merging fields
# If no rule matches ŌåÆ no rule-derived fields (profile + explicit fields still apply)

!! Post-creation actions

The `text` field of template tiddlers contains TW action widget markup. After the main tiddler is saved:

# All collected action text (from profile + matched rule templates) is concatenated
# A real `Widget` instance is created with `$tw.fakeDocument` (TW's server-side fake DOM)
# Variables set: all filter variables + `new-title` (the just-created tiddler's title)
# `invokeActionString()` executes the action widgets (e.g. `<$action-listops>`, `<$action-setfield>`)
# Any tiddlers modified by actions are detected and synced to disk

!! CLI deserializer internals

A `tiddlerdeserializer` module registers the MIME type `application/x-rimir-ext-connect`, enabling CLI import:

```
TIDDLYWIKI_CLI_MODE=1 npx tiddlywiki mywiki --import input.json application/x-rimir-ext-connect
```

Set `TIDDLYWIKI_CLI_MODE=1` so the filesystem-watcher skips startup and the process exits cleanly after import.

The deserializer reuses the same `resolve.js` pipeline as the POST route ŌĆö profiles, rules, templates, and post-creation actions all work identically. The key difference is persistence: since no syncer runs in CLI mode, the deserializer writes `.tid` files to disk directly using `$tw.utils.generateTiddlerFileInfo()` + `$tw.utils.saveTiddlerToFileSync()`, respecting `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` rules.

!!! Write target resolution

With `includeWikis`, `$tw.boot.wikiTiddlersPath` points to the wrapper's own `tiddlers/` directory ŌĆö not the included wiki's. The deserializer resolves the first `includeWikis` entry's path and writes to its `tiddlers/` subdirectory instead. This ensures files land in `mywiki/tiddlers/` where the running server's filesystem-watcher can detect them. The wrapper's `tiddlers/` dir holds only the plugin-disable tiddler and transient syncer artifacts (`$:/StoryList`).

!!! Self-save pattern

TW's `--import` flow normally expects the deserializer to return tiddler objects, which `wiki.importTiddler()` saves. But `importTiddler` has no action-execution hook, and we need to run post-creation actions that reference `new-title`. The deserializer handles everything internally (resolve, save, persist, execute actions) and returns `[]`. The `--import` command logs "0 tiddler(s) imported" but the deserializer logs its own success message.

!!! Action-modified tiddler persistence

After executing post-creation actions, the deserializer compares `changeCount` before/after to detect which tiddlers were modified by actions, and persists those to disk as well.

!! Filesystem persistence (POST fallback path)

Uses the syncer mismatch pattern: after `addTiddler()`, sets `$tw.syncer.tiddlerInfo[title].changeCount` to `wiki.getChangeCount() - 1`. The syncer detects the mismatch on its next tick and writes the `.tid` file to disk.

<$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/doc-template/templates/callout" type="info">
<$fill $name="body">
This is the inverse of the filesystem-watcher pattern, which sets `changeCount` to //match// the wiki to //prevent// syncer writes. Here we intentionally create a mismatch to //trigger// the write.
</$fill>
</$transclude>

---

!! Text-command extraction (outbound)

The outbound path extracts `@Target` commands from tiddler text and routes them to a watched folder on disk.

!!! Extraction flow

# User saves a tiddler in the browser (navigator widget triggers `th-saving-tiddler`)
# Hook checks if tiddler matches the configurable scan filter (`$:/config/rimir/text-command/scan-filter`)
# Text is parsed for `@Target` patterns using regexes built from the registered targets list
# For each command found: a command tiddler is created via `$tw.wiki.addTiddler()` with the outbox tag
# The command text in the original tiddler is replaced with a `<$tiddler>/<$transclude>` wrapper pointing to the view template
# The modified tiddler is returned from the hook

!!! Command tiddler structure

|!Field |!Value |
|`title` |`<OriginalTitle>/@<Target>/<timestamp>` |
|`tags` |Outbox tag (default: `ext-outbox`) |
|`text` |The extracted command text |
|`source` |Original tiddler title |
|`target` |Target name (e.g. `LLM`) |
|`command-text` |The extracted command text (also in `text`) |
|`status` |`pending` (updatable by external tools) |

!!! FileSystemPaths routing

A `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` entry routes outbox-tagged tiddlers to `tiddlers/ext-outbox/`:
```
[tag[ext-outbox]addprefix[ext-outbox/]]
```

External tools need only watch `mywiki/tiddlers/ext-outbox/`.

!!! Loop prevention

* Command tiddlers get the outbox tag, not the scan-filter tag ŌåÆ no re-extraction
* Modified original has transclusions instead of `@Target` text ŌåÆ no re-extraction on next save
* filesystem-watcher re-imports trigger `change` events, not navigator saves ŌåÆ hook doesn't fire

!!! Text-command syntax

''Single-line'': `@Target` followed by non-whitespace on the same line
```
@LLM summarize the above paragraph
```

''Multi-line'': `@Target` on its own line, content until closing `Target@`
```
@LLM
Please review the following code.
Focus on performance.
LLM@
```

!! Context rendering (outbound ŌåÆ external tool)

After a command tiddler lands in `ext-outbox/`, an external tool needs rendered context (source content, command text, metadata) to process the command.

!!! Rendering flow

# External tool detects new `.tid` file in `ext-outbox/`
# Runs: `npx tiddlywiki mywiki --render "[[CmdTitle]]" "[[context.txt]]" "text/plain" "$:/config/rimir/text-command/delegate"`
# Delegate template (`$:/config/rimir/text-command/delegate`) uses `:cascade` to select the right context template
# Cascade selectors (tagged `$:/tags/rimir/text-command/context-template`, sorted by `order`) are evaluated against the command tiddler
# First selector whose filter returns non-empty wins ŌåÆ returns a context render template title
# That template is transcluded, producing plain-text output
# External tool reads `mywiki/output/context.txt`
# Results come back via `POST /api/ext-connect/put-tiddler`

!!! Cascade pattern

The delegate template defines a `ctx.template()` function:

```
\function ctx.template() [all[current]] :cascade[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/text-command/context-template]sort[order]!is[draft]get[text]]
```

Each cascade selector tiddler's `text` is a filter expression that tests the command tiddler and returns a context template title if it matches. Example:

```
[all[current]get[target]match[LLM]then[$:/config/rimir/text-command/ctx/llm]]
```

!!! Adding a new target context

Create two tiddlers:

# ''Cascade selector'': tagged `$:/tags/rimir/text-command/context-template`, with an `order` field and a filter expression as `text`
# ''Context render template'': wikitext tiddler producing the plain-text output (`currentTiddler` = command tiddler)

No JS changes, no restart needed.

!! Design decisions

* ''TW filters over custom DSL'': template field values are real TW filter expressions ŌĆö composable, powerful, no custom parser needed
* ''`out.` prefix convention'': clean escape mechanism for reserved field names without inventing new syntax
* ''Action widgets for side effects'': TW's `invokeActionString()` works server-side with `$tw.fakeDocument` ŌĆö no DOM needed
* ''First-match rules'': ordered array, first match wins ŌĆö simple and predictable
* ''Template tiddlers in wiki store'': editable from browser, no restart needed for config changes
* ''CLI-primary, POST fallback'': CLI `--import` is the primary inbound path; the POST endpoint shares the same `resolve.js` pipeline but may be deprecated

